T1  - STATE DEPENDENT PRICING AND BUSINESS CYCLE ASYMMETRIES*
AU  - Devereux, Michael B.
AU  - Siu,             Henry E.
Y1  - 2007/02/01
PY  - 2007
DA  - 2007/02/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2007.00426.x
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
SP  - 281
EP  - 310
VL  - 48
IS  - 1
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2007.00426.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - We present a tractable, dynamic general equilibrium model of state-dependent pricing and study the response of output and prices to monetary policy shocks. We find important nonlinearities in these responses. For empirically relevant shocks, this generates substantially different predictions from time-dependent pricing. We also find a distinct asymmetry with state-dependent pricing: Prices respond more to positive shocks than they do to negative shocks. This is due to a strategic linkage between firms in the incentive for price adjustment. Our state-dependent model can account for business cycle asymmetries in output of the magnitude found in empirical studies.
ER  - 

